  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n- Monitoring transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collecting customer identification information\n- Understanding customer business activities\n- Verifying source of funds\n\n5. Regulatory Compliance\n- Following guidelines from agencies like FinCEN\n- Adhering to laws like the Bank Secrecy Act\n- Cooperating with law enforcement investigations\n\n6. Screening and Monitoring\n- Checking customer names against sanctions lists\n- Tracking unusual transaction patterns\n- Using automated monitoring systems\n\nFailure to comply with these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal charges.",
